<section xml:id="sec-real-numbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Real Numbers</title>
    <p>
        A real number is any number that can be placed on a number line. It includes:
    </p>
    <p>
        <ol marker="i)">
            <li>
                <p>
                   Whole numbers like <m>0, 1, 2</m>.
 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Integers like <m>-3, -2, -1, 0, 1, 2</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Fractions like <m>\frac{1}{2}, \frac{2}{3}, \frac{1}{3}</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Decimals like <m>0.2,4.5,-2.6</m>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                   Irrational numbers like <m>\sqrt{2}, \pi</m> 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </p>
    <p>
        Real numbers include all numbers we use in daily life, they can be positive, negative, or zero. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{NOTE:}</m> Real numbers do not include imaginary numbers like the square root of <m>-1</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{blue}\text{Why do we study real numbers?}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        We use real numbers to manage money while budgeting or shopping for items, to measure ingredients when cooking, to track time and distance while traveling, and to understand data on digital devices. 
    </p>
